In [5]:
#This function helps with drawing decision trees using the pydotplus and graphviz libraries
def print_tree(estimator, features, class_names=None, filled=True):
    tree = estimator
    names = features
    color = filled
    classn = class_names
    
    dot_data = StringIO()
    export_graphviz(estimator, out_file=dot_data, feature_names=features,\
                    class_names=classn, filled=filled)
    graph = pplus.graph_from_dot_data(dot_data.getvalue())
    return(graph)

In [6]:
df_elsalvador_baseline = pd.read_csv('WBdata-covid-shared/ElSalvador-2016-baseline.csv',encoding = "cp1252") #encoding = "utf-8"
df_elsalvador_covid = pd.read_csv('WBdata-covid-shared/ElSalvador-2020-covid.csv',encoding = "cp1252")
df_guatemala_baseline = pd.read_csv('WBdata-covid-shared/Guatemala-2017-baseline.csv',encoding = "cp1252")
df_guatemala_covid = pd.read_csv('WBdata-covid-shared/Guatemala-2020-covid.csv')
df_honduras_baseline = pd.read_csv('WBdata-covid-shared/Honduras-2016-baseline.csv',encoding = "cp1252")
df_honduras_covid = pd.read_csv('WBdata-covid-shared/Honduras-2020-covid.csv')
df_nicaragua_baseline = pd.read_csv('WBdata-covid-shared/Nicaragua-2016-baseline.csv',encoding = "cp1252")
df_nicaragua_covid = pd.read_csv('WBdata-covid-shared/Nicaragua-2020-covid.csv')

Please note:

  • While trying to read the csv through Pandas and load it into memory/DataFrame object, I got below error:
    UnicodeDecodeError: 'utf-8' codec can't decode byte 0xf3 in position 11: invalid continuation byte

  • I tried adding the encoding parameter value of read_csv() as "utf-8" but still didnt work as I got similar error:
    UnicodeDecodeError: 'utf-8' codec can't decode byte 0xb4 in position 2612: invalid start byte

  • I have resolved the issue by doing research and setting the read_csv() encoding parameter value as "cp1252". Ref link:
    https://stackoverflow.com/questions/45529507/unicodedecodeerror-utf-8-codec-cant-decode-byte-0x96-in-position-35-invalid

According to the narrative I have chosen, I would do the following for further pre-processing:-

  • filter the dataFrame by considering the columns pertaining to
    Section D of the baseline survey - "Sales and Supplies" and
    Sections B,C of the covid survey - "Sales", "Production"
  • further filter the respective dataFrames based on Industry chosen “Retail services” and
  • then merge both baseline and covid dataFrames on the column ‘idstd’
  • drop the columns which arent necessary for the analysis

Defining functions
get_numerical_val_ordered_categories(), get_numerical_val_ordered_categories_2()

which would return the numerical value corresponding to the Ordered Category
For columns: 'd30a','d30b','d10','d11', 'n3','d3a','d3b','d3c','d2','LACd10a','LACd10b','LACd10c','LACd10d','LACd10e','LACd7','LACd8','LACd9','LACd11','LACd12','d1a3','d12a','d12b','d13'

  • Please note: Some of the numerical values have been assigned based on the terminology in the survey (Page 16, 17) and others assigned like No - 0, Yes - 1 and some others as per Degree of Positivity, based on the context
  • Does not apply - implies that there is no obstacle so assigning the value 0 instead of -7. Moreover, if we assign -7, then this will be like an outlier and the ML model may be skewed. Its also not good to remove such rows as the ML model wont be having sufficient data points to work with.
  • Similarly, No internal shipments made implies that there are No losses, so it would be assigned value 0 instead of -7 .
    Dont know means there may or may not be losses but the company couldnt estimate/provide those values in the survey - returning NaN instead of -9 : again thinking about the row being an outlier from ML model point of view. Similarly, Does not apply means that column is not relevant for that particular row/record, so returning NaN instead of 0 or neg value.
In [58]:
def get_numerical_val_ordered_categories(value):
    if value == 'No obstacle':
        return 0
    elif value == 'Minor obstacle':
        return 1
    elif value == 'Moderate obstacle':
        return 2
    elif value == 'Major obstacle':
        return 3
    elif value == 'Very severe obstacle':
        return 4
    else:
        return np.NaN#return 0 #-7 This is for 'Does not apply'
In [59]:
def get_numerical_val_2(value):
    if value in ['No losses','No internal shipments made (does not apply)','Not in business three years ago']:#if value in ['No losses','No internal shipments made (does not apply)', "Don't know (spontaneous)",'Not in business three years ago']:
        return 0
    elif (pd.isnull(value) != True) and (value != "Don't know (spontaneous)"):
        return float(value) #Converting and returning the numerical value
    elif (pd.isnull(value) != True) and (value == "Don't know (spontaneous)"):
        return np.NaN
    else:
        return value
In [60]:
def get_numerical_val_3(value):
    if (pd.isnull(value) != True) and (value == 'No'):#if (pd.isnull(value) != True) and (value == 'No' or value == 'Does not apply' or value == "Don't know (spontaneous)"):
        return 0
    elif (pd.isnull(value) != True) and (value == 'Yes'):
        return 1
    elif (pd.isnull(value) != True) and (value == 'Does not apply' or value == "Don't know (spontaneous)"):
        return np.NaN
    else:#elif value is None:
        return value
In [61]:
def get_numerical_val_4(value):
    if (pd.isnull(value) != True) and (value == 'Decrease' or value == 'Decrease capacity' or \
                                       value == 'Permanently closed'):
        return -1
    elif (pd.isnull(value) != True) and (value == 'Stay the same' or value == 'Capacity stayed the same' or \
                                         value == 'Remain the same' or value == 'Temporarily closed'):
                                         #value == 'Does not apply' or value == "Don't know (spontaneous)" or value == '-7'):
        return 0
    elif (pd.isnull(value) != True) and (value == 'Increase' or value == 'Increase capacity' \
                                        or value == 'Open'):
        return 1
    elif (pd.isnull(value) != True) and (value == 'Does not apply' or \
                                         value == "Don't know (spontaneous)" or value == '-7'):
        return np.NaN
    else:#elif value is None:
        return value

def get_numerical_val_5(value):
    if value < 1:
        return 0
    else:
        return 1

Initially assigned 0 to new variables when value is Dont know or Does not apply in original variable. Later changed it by assigning NaN, which increased the number of NaN values to the existing null values in csv
Also, each row in the dataFrame corresponds to a company and it is tricky to fill the missing data. We cannot use median or mean values to fill the missing data for any column as this would apply to all rows wherever null value is present such as dfSoy.fillna({'precip' : dfSoy['precip'].mean(), 'temp':dfSoy['temp'].median()}, inplace=True)
because the survey is not for a single entity but multiple entities/companies and we cannot generalize the sales figure or the obstacles faced, percentage sales direct, indirect exports etc. if the value is Dont know because all these attributes are company-specific, therefore cant be generalized per se.

In [188]:
df_elsalvador_bl_co_merged3.fillna(0,inplace=True)

Each row in the dataFrame corresponds to a company and it is tricky to fill the missing data. We cannot use median or mean values to fill the missing data for any column as this would apply to all rows wherever null value is present such as dfSoy.fillna({'precip' : dfSoy['precip'].mean(), 'temp':dfSoy['temp'].median()}, inplace=True)
because the survey is not for a single entity but multiple entities/companies and we cannot generalize the sales figure or the obstacles faced, percentage sales direct, indirect exports etc. if the value is Dont know because all these attributes are company-specific, therefore cant be generalized per se.

Initially assigned 0 to new variables when value is Dont know or Does not apply in original variable. Later changed it by assigning NaN, which increased the number of NaN values to the existing null values in csv
Also, each row in the dataFrame corresponds to a company and it is tricky to fill the missing data. We cannot use median or mean values to fill the missing data for any column as this would apply to all rows wherever null value is present such as dfSoy.fillna({'precip' : dfSoy['precip'].mean(), 'temp':dfSoy['temp'].median()}, inplace=True)
because the survey is not for a single entity but multiple entities/companies and we cannot generalize the sales figure or the obstacles faced, percentage sales direct, indirect exports etc. if the value is Dont know because all these attributes are company-specific, therefore cant be generalized per se.

In [244]:
df_honduras_bl_co_merged3.fillna(0,inplace=True)

Each row in the dataFrame corresponds to a company and it is tricky to fill the missing data. We cannot use median or mean values to fill the missing data for any column as this would apply to all rows wherever null value is present such as dfSoy.fillna({'precip' : dfSoy['precip'].mean(), 'temp':dfSoy['temp'].median()}, inplace=True)
because the survey is not for a single entity but multiple entities/companies and we cannot generalize the sales figure or the obstacles faced, percentage sales direct, indirect exports etc. if the value is Dont know because all these attributes are company-specific, therefore cant be generalized per se.

Out[256]:
20.565137526878853

Interpretation: Our model is deviant from the actual values by about 20.56%, on average when using the test data. Moreover, It depends on how good the accuracy has to be depending on the context.
